Homework 3¶

Michał Orzyłowski¶

Dataset¶

I decided to use a churn dataset for this task - the same one as in Homework 1. It is a dataset relating characteristics of telephony account features and usage and whether or not the customer churned.

Selected observations decomposition¶

I selected two observations which have opposite predicted scores - observations number 33 and 34. The first one has probability of churn equal to 0.87 and the other one 0.04. Explained model is a random forest classifier. Decomposition of observations is visible below. We can see that in both cases total_day_minutes and total_day_charge were crucial features here.

Stability assessment¶

From plots showing LIME behavior for different seeds it is clear that algorithm is not completely stable. However, the most important features stay the same even if their impact on prediction varies.

LIME comparison for random forest and logistic regression¶

For comparison I use the same model as in the Homework 1 - logistic regression. LIME shows that regression model uses total_day_minutes as a top predictor but it also looks at some other variables like total_intl_minutes, total_eve_minutes or total_night_minutes.

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

randomForest = RandomForestClassifier().fit(x, y)
randomForestExplainer = dx.Explainer(randomForest, x, y)

In [60]:
for seed in range(4):
    random.seed(seed)
    np.random.seed(seed)
    exp = randomForestExplainer.predict_surrogate(obs1)
    exp.plot(return_figure=True)
    plt.title(f'Explanation for first observation (id=33) assuming random seed is {seed}')

forest_proba = randomForest.predict_proba(selected_x)
reg_proba = logisticRegression.predict_proba(selected_x)

for i in range(selected_x.shape[0]):
    exp_forest = randomForestExplainer.predict_surrogate(selected_x.iloc[i])
    exp_forest.plot(return_figure=True)
    plt.title(f"Random forest explanation (churn probability={forest_proba[i, 1]})")

    exp_reg = logisticRegressionExplainer.predict_surrogate(selected_x.iloc[i])
    exp_reg.plot(return_figure=True)
    plt.title(f"Logistic regression explanation (churn probability={reg_proba[i, 1]:.2f})")
